                <head>No. 176.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Blaine</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Angell</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1881-08-30">
                            <hi rend="italic">August</hi> 30, 1881</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 123.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your dispatch No. 173, of the 18th of June last,
                    respecting the immunity granted to Protestant Chinese converts, has been
                    received and read with much interest.</p>
                <p>The Christian world cannot but be deeply impressed by this action of the Chinese
                    Government, which manifests so liberal and just a disposition toward such of its
                    subjects as are led to adopt the Christian faith.</p>
                <p>A copy of your dispatch has been communicated for the information of the American
                    Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions at Boston.</p>
                <p>I am, sir,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>JAMES G. BLAINE.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
